Here we have to solve the equation \displaystyle{20}={120}\cdot{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{5.6}}}}.

    First, divide by 120. 


    \displaystyle\frac{{20}}{{120}}={\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{5.6}}}} 


    Then apply the \displaystyle{\log} to both sides. 


    \displaystyle{\log{{\left(\frac{{20}}{{120}}\right)}}}={\log{{\left({\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{5.6}}}}\right)}}} 


    Now bring the power down as a multiple of the right side. 


    \displaystyle{\log{{\left(\frac{{20}}{{120}}\right)}}}=\frac{{t}}{{5.6}}\cdot{\log{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}} 


    Multiply by 5.6. 


    \displaystyle{5.6}\cdot{\log{{\left(\frac{{20}}{{120}}\right)}}}={t}\cdot{\log{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}} 


    Divide by \displaystyle{\log{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}. 


    \displaystyle{5.6}\cdot\frac{{\log{{\left(\frac{{20}}{{120}}\right)}}}}{{\log{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}}={t} 


    Accoring to my calculator, starting with 120 mg of caffeine and a half-life of 5.6 hours, there will be 20 mg remaining in this person's system after about 14.48 hours.
